# Agent Self-Review Checklist

Before committing any change, verify the following. This applies to both human and AI-authored code.

## Pre-Commit Checks
1. No `print()` or `breakpoint()` left in library code (`src/`). Use `self.logger` instead.
2. No commented-out code blocks. Delete dead code; git has history.
3. No `TODO` or `FIXME` without a linked issue or rationale in the comment.
4. All new public functions and classes have Google-style docstrings.
5. All new functions have type annotations on parameters and return types.

## Quality Gate (must pass before commit)
```
uv run ruff check .
uv run ruff format --check .
uv run pyright
uv run pytest -x -m "not long"
```

## Commit Hygiene
- Use conventional commit prefixes: `feat:`, `fix:`, `test:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `ci:`.
- Keep commits atomic — one logical change per commit.
- Commit message should explain *why*, not just *what*.

## Distribution of Knowledge
- Important and validated findings shall be distributed appropriately using first principles into skills, rules, docs, and docstrings.
- If a pattern is reusable, capture it in the relevant `.cursor/rules/` or `.cursor/skills/` file.
